The world of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian aircraft, crashing two of them into the towers of the World Trade Center in New York, hitting the Pentagon with a third, and causing the fourth aircraft to crash in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believed would have been the White House or another American government building in Washington, DC.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 were from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of an operation planned, organized, and carried out by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were reported killed, and more than 6,000 injured.
The majority were American, although citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions in Madrid's trains in March 2004, then the attack on London's public transport system in July 2005.
Terrorists affiliated with the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels' airport in March 2016, and instigated a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to ram into pedestrians).
For that reason, neither the United States nor any of their allies has ever suffered an attack of comparable magnitude to those of September 11 – which are without measure.
Therefore, it is necessary to question: Beyond immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why terrorists have not succeeded in carrying out other major attacks.
Following the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Palmost all governments around the world have implemented control procedures making it harder for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, policing, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, which constitutes one of the rare areas where states, often at odds with each other, are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not differentiate between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The days of romanticizing individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause are over.
It is not to say that terrorism has ceased to claim the lives of tens of thousands of people each year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of ongoing conflicts (mainly in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, of the 9/11 type, against major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization's leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by American special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the 9/11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution on the horizon.
The possibility of another 9/11 cannot be ruled out either, even though the U.S. government recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" for the country existed domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army expressed after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today we were unlucky, but remember it only takes one lucky day for us."
You will always need one."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists will acquire nuclear material, or manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, at which point terrorism could determine the era.
Pour l’heure, ce n’est pas le cas.
Le 11 septembre a pour autant marqué un tournant historique, avec un profond impact sur la politique étrangère américaine des 20 dernières années.
Si les attentats n’ont pas débouché sur une ère du terrorisme mondial, ils ont bel et bien engendré la fameuse guerre mondiale contre la terreur, avec des conséquences majeures dans le comportement des États-Unis à travers le monde, l’image de l’Amérique aux yeux du monde, et la manière dont de nombreux Américains ont fini par considérer la politique étrangère de leur pays.
La saga a débuté en Afghanistan.
Peu après les attentats du 11 septembre, les États-Unis ont proposé un choix aux talibans, qui contrôlaient alors le gouvernement afghan : livrer les responsables d’Al-Qaïda sur le point de quitter le pays, et coupables d’avoir organisé les attentats du 11 septembre, ou mettre en péril leur règne.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, US intelligence and military officials collaborated with an unstructured Afghan tribal confederation known as the Northern Alliance to oust the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control, however, was never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda have fled to the neighboring Pakistan, where they have gradually rebuilt their strength and resumed military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On their part, the United States did not do enough to build up an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Au lieu de cela, America has reinforced its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, American intervention in Afghanistan mobilized over 100,000 U.S. soldiers.
Over more than two decades, the cost of operations has amounted to over $2 trillion, resulting in the loss of over 2,300 American lives, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than America, which had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined for indefinite deadlock by 2020.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to enter into war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "giant impotent and pitiful."
This led some members of the administration (chief among them Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (which turned out not to be the case) according to most protagonists.
Others sought to propagate democracy in Iraq, then throughout the entire Middle East, considering that such an approach was not only feasible but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
Déclenchée in March 2003, the Iraq War did not unfold as the Bush administration, along with numerous Congressional members (including Joe Biden, then a senator) and global leaders who had approved it, had hoped or anticipated.
The United States was not prepared for the key events that were to follow.
Military victories initially achieved indeed allowed for the ousting of the government, but soon gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army, and to exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs, worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, like Afghanistan, Iraq demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a cost and within reasonable timeframes.
In the end, the United States was forced to reinforce its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States has spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much greater human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, far more wounded, and an explosive rise in suicide rates among American military personnel (from Iraq as well as Afghanistan).
This total does not include deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for which estimates vary widely, but which certainly number in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other ways.
No proof has ever shown Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – was revealed to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, a war-torn Iraq has become synonymous with a rising Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence in Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
Pendant que les États-Unis s’impliquaient intensément au Moyen-Orient et en Asie du Sud, régions qui manquent de grandes puissances présentes et de dynamisme économique, l’équilibre géopolitique s’est déplacé en défaveur des États-Unis, à la fois en Europe et en Asie de l’Est, en raison de l’émergence d’une Russie plus agressive, ainsi que d’une Chine plus forte et plus affirmée.
La guerre mondiale contre le terrorisme ne pouvait pas fournir et n’a pas fourni aux États-Unis de boussole dans leur approche de politique étrangère à l’égard d’une rivalité renouvelée entre grandes puissances.
Les guerres menées à la suite du 11 septembre ont également entraîné d’importantes conséquences intérieures pour les États-Unis.
Elles ont ébranlé la confiance dans un pays qui était sorti de la guerre froide fort d’une puissance prépondérante historiquement sans précédent, et mis à mal l’unité nationale qui avait fait surface au lendemain immédiat des attentats.
Les coûts et les échecs associés à ces guerres ont par ailleurs alimenté l’opposition à un rôle mondial majeur et durable des États-Unis, donnant naissance à une nouvelle tendance isolationniste.
Similarly, this warlike propensity, associated with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted American confidence in elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and less inclined to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, which has generally largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
With hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less globalization of terrorism than fears of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distances and borders mattered little in the era of globalization.
Nothing remains local for long nowadays, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis with origins in poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since it appeared in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, which itself is the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events has come to a close, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly driven from power; in recent weeks, they have reclaimed it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will revert to their old ways and once again become a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
Ce que nous savons, en revanche, c’est que le terrorisme reste une caractéristique de notre monde.
Il ne définira pas l’avenir, mais demeurera l’un des aspects visibles d’une mondialisation qui pour sa part le détermine d’ores et déjà.
